# SPARC DLR Webhook Update Walkthrough

We have successfully rebuilt the DLR integration to accurately parse SPARC's varying payload shapes!

## What We Achieved

We updated the inbound logic so that the connector now natively "speaks" the exact JSON SPARC will throw at it via the webhook, without altering any data sent upstream to MoEngage.

> [!NOTE]
> **No MoEngage Output Was Changed.** As requested, the way we send data *back* to MoEngage remains 100% frozen as it was originally defined. MoEngage will receive exactly the `[ { status, callback_data, timestamp, error_message } ]` array they expect. The SMS logic also remains completely untouched.

### 1. Robust SPARC Parsing
Your dumps showed that SPARC sometimes nests their payloads heavily (e.g., inside an `eventData` wrapper containing an `entity`), and sometimes dumps it relatively flat. 

We built a resilient parser in `dlrController.js` and `dlrMapper.js`:
```javascript
const eventRoot = sparcEvent.eventData || sparcEvent;
const entity = eventRoot.entity || {};

const sparcStatus = (entity.eventType || '').toUpperCase();
const callbackData = sparcEvent.seqId || sparcEvent.seq_id || eventRoot.seqId;
```
This guarantees the script will safely find the payload regardless of the specific event type.

### 2. Exact Status Mapping
We updated the mapping dictionaries in `dlrMapper.js` to match exactly the string statuses you observed from SPARC:
- `"SEND_MESSAGE_SUCCESS"` translates to `"RCS_SENT"`
- `"MESSAGE_DELIVERED"` translates to `"RCS_DELIVERED"`
- `"MESSAGE_READ"` translates to `"RCS_READ"`
- `"SEND_MESSAGE_FAILURE"` translates to `"RCS_DELIVERY_FAILED"`

### 3. Timestamp Conversion
SPARC sends ISO strings like `2026-03-28T15:21:39.260922Z`. MoEngage expects 10-digit epoch timestamps (e.g., `1711617699`). Our parsing engine seamlessly intercepts `entity.sendTime` from SPARC, converts it to epoch seconds, and attaches it correctly so MoEngage understands the delivery time.

### 4. Failure Messaging
When we intercept a `SEND_MESSAGE_FAILURE`, we dig specifically into `entity.error.message` (e.g., `"User Not Found"`) and safely pull it out to attach as `error_message` for MoEngage.

